Leader developmentA review of more than a century's studies on psychological aspects of leadership reveals a notable absence of comprehensive and
methodical discussion and research on developmental psychological aspects of leaders (Avolio, 1999, 2005; Avolio & Gibbons, 1988;
Day, Zaccaro, & Halpin, 2004; Klonsky,1983; Kuhnert & Lewis,1987; London, 2002; McCauley, & Van Velsor, 2004; Popper & Mayseless,
2002; Zacharatos, Barling, & Kelloway, 2000).
Most evidence on the development of leaders has been supplied by historians who studied the lives of outstanding leaders (e.g.,
Bullock,1991; Burns,1956). Characteristically, these studies (1) focus on exceptional leaders who are of great interest to historians, and
(2) analyze their development mainly from a psychoanalytic viewpoint (Burns, 1978). Such studies are clearly limited with regard to
the possibility of generalization. This criticism is often directed at psychoanalytical research in general (Meadow, 1996), but it is even
more relevant in the case of historical studies of outstanding (usually political) personages (Burns,1978). They do not necessarily shed
light on leaders of local communities, organizational units, social frameworks, and the like, namely those who might be described as
“leaders in everyday life.”
A more comprehensive analysis of leaders' development is to be found in the works of scholars who discuss psychological
processes that may generate patterns of development toward leadership (Aberbach, 1995; Kets de Vries, 1989; Popper, 2000;
Zaleznik, 1992). These authors identiﬁed in some leaders similar types of socialization in early childhood, which, they claim, may
indicate distinct patterns of development of leadership. For instance, the biographies of several leaders reveal a close relationship
with the mother (sometimes as the mother's favorite child), expectations of greatness projected by at least one of the parents, and
exposure to esteemed authorityﬁgures in the family or in social circles close to the family (Burns, 1978).
