Gibbons (1986)and Avolio and Gibbons (1988)examined the developmental process of leaders through in-depth personal
interviews conducted with a sample of senior managers, who were asked to talk about events and experiences in their past from
childhood to maturity. These authors enumerated seven factors in leaders' development, which can be clustered into three groups
of variables: 1. Family conditions in which the individual was raised; 2. Experiences of leadership; 3. Openness to experiences.
Although Avolio and Gibbons' work contributes conceptually and empirically to the study of leaders' development, their
conclusions are limited since their work is based on interviewing sixteen transformational leaders; without a comparative
perspective, possible unique features in leaders' development cannot be seen. These can only be identiﬁed and examined through
comparison with a population of“non-leaders”. Moreover, the different factors in Avolio and Gibbons' study do not reﬂect the same
theoretical entity. While openness to experiences is a personality variable, family conditions and leadership experiences represent
environmental and situational variables.
Recently these limitations served as a point of departure in the planning of a series of studies comparing a group of leaders
with a group of non-leaders on a battery of personality traits and developmental variables (Amit, Popper, Gal, Maman, & Lisak,
2008; Popper, Amit, Gal, Sinai, & Lisak, 2004). Leaders were found to be distinctly higher than non-leaders in self-conﬁdence as
measured by level of trait anxiety (Popper et al., 2004). (Trait anxiety, according toSpielberger (1972), differs from state anxiety
in that it is a personality characteristic.) Theseﬁndings are congruent withJudge, Bono, Ilies, and Gerhardt's (2002)ﬁndings on
a negative correlation between neuroticism and leadership emergence (−.24). Other studies found that leaders (more than
non-leaders) reported experiences of leadership roles at school and in social settings (Amit et al., 2008; Hall, Lord, Ritter, Swee,
& Dubois, 2004; Maman, 2005). Leaders also proved higher than non-leaders in openness to experiences as measured by the
NEO Personality Inventory of the Five-Factor model (Costa & McCrae, 1992a; Judge & Bono, 2000; Judge et al., 2002; Popper et
al., 2004).
The difference between leaders and non-leaders in willingness to undertake leadership roles is congruent with theﬁndings of studies
on general development. For example, a correlation of .43 was found between openness to experiences and experience seeking
(Zuckerman, Kuhlman, Joireman, Teta, & Kraft,1993); a high correlation (.42) was found between openness to experiences andﬂexibility
(McCrae, Costa, & Piedmont,1993), and a negative correlation (−.56) was found between openness to experience and tough-mindedness
(Conn & Rieke, 1994). The variable openness to experiences may also contribute to the understanding of the social dimension that is so
relevant to close leadership.Guttman (1995)found that problems in interpersonal relationships were associated more with individuals
who were classiﬁed as being less open to experiences. Similarﬁndings were reported byKitron (1976)and Gilbert (1991).
Popper et al. (2004)and Amit et al. (2008)showed that level of trait anxiety and openness to experiences carry the greatest
weight in predicting leadership potential and leadership development in regression equations. Theseﬁndings indicate the
existence of basic components in the development of leaders— personality components formed in early childhood (Popper &
Mayseless, 2002, 2007that inﬂuence the scope and intensity of leadership-learning processes generated by leadership experiences
(Amit et al., 2008; Maman, 2005).
The paucity of theoretical and empirical material on leaders' development from early childhood is surprising in view of the
substantial theoretical and methodological progress made in psychological knowledge, particularly in understanding the individual's
inner world as shaped in early childhood. The monumental contributions ofFreud (1920), Er
ikson (1959) , Jung (1986), Kohut (1971),
Bowlby (1969), and many others have advanced our understanding of the growth of internal representations that guide the
individual's emotions and behaviors throughout his/her life. Empirical research in developmental psychology has likewise made
enormous progress in characterization of the personality and its development from childhood to old age (Bowlby,1969; Cassidy,1994;
Hazan & Shaver, 1987). Yet, this knowledge has not found expression in the empirical study of leadership psychology (Popper, 2005;
Popper & Mayseless, 2002).
This assumption that has been the basis for many if not most studies in developmental psychology (Schaffer, 2000) may well apply
also to the development of individuals as leaders. Findings on the central importance of level of trait anxiety and openness to
experiences in a comparison of leaders and non-leaders can provide a sound basis for examining the inﬂuence of these basic
personality components, which are formed in early childhood and may be hypothesized as exercising a considerable impact on the
learning of leadership in maturity. This appears to be a promising direction,ﬁrst because of the important part played by variables
formed in early childhood on the adult's development, and secondly because it may be inferred from studies conducted speciﬁcally on
openness to experiences. For example,Costa and McCrae (1992b)showed that openness to experience as measured in early childhood
remains stable over time. They reported a correlation of .66 between two measures of openness over a period of 24 years.Finn (1986)
reported a correlation of .62 on intellectual interest across a gap of 30 years.Costa and McCrae (1992b)reported that despite the
stereotype that adults are characterized by more conservatism and rigidity, analysis of the means of openness to experiences indicated
a slight and non-signiﬁcant decrease at a more advanced age.
Accordingly, differences between leaders and non-leaders in levels of trait anxiety and openness to experiences seem especially
important from the point of view of development. Data on leaders' more extensive experience of leadership roles in childhood
(Amit et al., 2008; Maman, 2005; Popper et al., 2004) may be explained by the leaders' lower level of trait anxiety and higher level
of openness to experiences. That is, the basic capacity for learning and development that germinates in early childhood meets the
opportunity — the relevant social context for the manifestation of leadership.
The inevitable question is this: What determines the low level of trait anxiety and the openness to experiences which, in our
opinion, form the psychological substructure for the development of leadership via experience of leadership roles?
Bowlby's (1969)attachment theory may provide an answer to this question because (1) it deals with early childhood, (2) it permits
operationalization of variables discussed at the conceptual level in psychodynamic theories, (3) it is considered today the most
important developmental theory (Cassidy & Shaver, 1999), (4) it is based on empirical support of greater scope than any other
750 M. Popper, K. Amit / The Leadership Quarterly 20 (2009) 749–763
developmental theory (Cassidy & Shaver, 1999), and (5) some promising initial attempts have been made to link attachment theory
with leadership (Davidovitz, Mikulincer, Shaver, Iszak & Popper, 2007; Mikulincer & Florian, 1995; Popper, Mayseless, & Castelnovo,
2000). We now examine the theory and its implications for the present discussion.
1. Overview of attachment theory
Based on ethological, evolutionary, and control systems concepts, attachment theory postulates an innate bio-social behavioral
system in the infant, the purpose of which is to maintain proximity between the infant and its primary caregiver. The evolutionary
purpose of this behavioral system is to promote the infant's survival through protection by a“stronger and wiser” ﬁgure, given that
it cannot survive on its own.
According to attachment theory, adults have a complementary behavioral system, whose main function is protection of the
infant. This system is activated when threat impends. The child uses the caregiver as a secure base from which to explore, and
periodically checks to ascertain the availability of the attachmentﬁgure. When a threat arises (e.g., hunger, loud noises) the
attachment system is activated and the child seeks the protection of the caregiver, who then serves as a safe haven.
Differences in the ability to signal the need and desire for closeness, and especially differences in the caregiver's responsiveness,
generate variations in babies' attachment styles. It is assumed that from infancy onward children form an internal working model,
which includes internalization and representations of major aspects of their attachment relationships with their caregivers (Bowlby,
1969, 1973; Bretherton, 1985). These aspects include perception of the self as (un)worthy of love and attention, and perception of the
attachmentﬁgure as (un)willing and (un)able to attend to the attachment needs when they arise. The internal working model guides
the interpretation and planning of interpersonal transactions with the caregiver, and later with other importantﬁgures. Atﬁrst it
involves a representation of the speciﬁc relationship with a speciﬁc caregiver. Later, following repeated experiences, the model
increasingly becomes a part of the child's developing personality and turns into a more abstract, generalized representation of the self
and others (Bretherton, 1985; Collins & Read, 1990).
On the basis of Bowlby's theory,Ainsworth, Blehar, Waters, and Wall (1978)identiﬁed three styles of infant attachment, one secure,
and two insecure, namely ambivalent and avoidant. These styles were later also identiﬁed in childhood and adulthood (see reviews by
Solomon & George, 1999). As summarized in a review chapter byCassidy (1999), the internal working model of secure individuals
includes a basic trust in their caregiver and conﬁdence that he or she will be available, responsive, and helpful when needed. With this
assurance, they are bold in their explorations of the world, and able both to rely on themselves and to turn to others when in need. In
contrast, the internal working model of the anxious/ambivalent pattern is characterized by uncertainty as to whether the parent or
caregiver will be available, responsive, or helpful when called upon. Avoidant attachment is a pattern in which individuals have no
conﬁdence that they will receive care when they seek it; on the contrary, they expect to be rebuffed. Thus, secure individuals have more
chances of becoming self-conﬁdent and open than do insecure ones.
Many studies bear witness to the stability of these internal models over the individual's lifetime (Cassidy, 1994), and the relation
between the inner world formed in infancy (attachment style) and feelings, behaviors and relationships that reach expression in
maturity (e.g.,Cicchetti, Toth, & Lynch, 1995; Mikulincer & Orbach, 1995). Research in the early 1990s addressed both the long-term
stability of attachment patterns and the role that sensitive care plays in the formation of attachment bonds. Presenting initialﬁndings
from the Minnesota longitudinal project,Elicker, Englund, and Sroufe (1992)reported that assessments of attachment during infancy
successfully predicted speciﬁc patterns of social behavior in adolescence, just as Bowlby had anticipated. Speciﬁcally, they afﬁrmed a
signiﬁcant relationship between secure attachment as assessed in infancy and leadership ratings by observers at a weekend camp
organized in adolescence, some 15 years later (Englund, Levy, Hyson, & Sroufe, 2000). Similar conclusions were reported by
correlational research (e.g.,Isabella, 1993; Isabella & Belsky, 1991). A great deal of research using Hazan and Shaver's self-report
measures has tested and conﬁrmed fundamental predictions of attachment theory as formulated by Bowlby (Collins & Read, 1990;
F
eeney, Noller, & Callan,1994; Simpson, Rholes & Nelligan,1992). Hazan and Shaver (1987)found that people with a secure attachment
style were more capable of intimacy and closeness in romantic relations than those with an insecure style. Similarﬁndings were
reported byMayseless, Sharabani, and Sagi (1997)in connection with parent–child relations and friendship. Recently, research based
on attachment theory has been expanded to the spheres of work orientations (Hazan & Shaver, 1990), and particularly leadership in
organizations (e.g.,Keller, 2003; Keller & Cacioppe, 2001). The researchers' assumption was that leadership also involves relationships
between the leader and his/her followers, so a theory predicting the quality of relationships can also be relevant to leadership.
Popper and Mayseless (2007)argue that in terms of attachment theory, leaders adopt the role of stronger and wiser caregivers
and provide a safe haven and a secure base for their followers.
Descriptions of effective leaders in everyday life in the scientiﬁc literature (e.g.,House & Howell,1992; Howell,1988; Shamir, House,
&A r t h u r ,1 9 9 3) closely resemble descriptions of security-promoting attachmentﬁgures. Effective leaders are sensitive and responsive
to their followers' needs; they provide group members with advice, guidance, and emotional and instrumental resources; they support
their followers' creativity, initiative, and autonomy; they enhance their self-worth and self-efﬁcacy; they support their followers' desire
to meet new challenges and acquire new skills. These leaders can be viewed as sensitive and responsive caregivers who provide their
followers with a sense of security and a platform for personal growth and development (Mayseless & Popper, 2007). Such leaders must
have the ego resources required for taking on these kinds of leadership roles. The argument is that secure individuals have the
psychological base required for such leadership whereas insecure personality types lack it.Mikulincer and Florian (1995)found that
individuals deﬁned as having a secure attachment style were assessed as more suitable for ofﬁcer roles in sociometric evaluations by
their peers on a military course.Popper et al. (2000)found a signiﬁcant positive correlation between transformational leadership and a
secure attachment style.
