In sum, attachment theory appears to supply the integrative theoretical framework for characterizing the development of the basic
components described in the introduction. Since attachment styles predict abilities in the affective social domain, as well as curiosity
and daring (Cassidy & Shaver, 1999), presumably they evince operational expression in level of trait anxiety and openness to
experiences. Speciﬁcally, the argument here is that attachment styles, by deﬁnition and nature, can predict levels of trait anxiety and
openness to experiences, which, as stated, are the basic components for the later development of leadership via experiences. The
research question, then, is this: Does a secure attachment style predict low trait anxiety and high openness to experiences, which are
the psychological substructure necessary for learning leadership via experience? And if so, to what extent does trait anxiety level and
openness to experiences predict leadership experience?
This argument can be presented through a general causal model suggesting that secure attachment style inﬂuences trait
anxiety level and openness to experiences, and these two variables in turn inﬂuence the dependent variable. We tested the
argument using structural equation modeling (SEM). FollowingHoyle's (1995)recommendations for a simpliﬁed presentation of
the SEM model, we show inFig. 1the general conceptual causal model.
The two preliminary hypotheses in this study relate to an argument represented by lines H1 and H2 in the general model (Fig. 1).
H1. A negative correlation will be found between secure attachment style and a high level of trait anxiety.
H2. A positive correlation will be found between secure attachment style and openness to experiences.
2. Inﬂuence of the basic components on the development of leaders via experience
Substantiation of these hypotheses would lead to examination of the inﬂuence of these relations on the future development of
leaders. The general hypothesis is that trait anxiety and openness to experiences are variables affecting the number and scope of
leadership experiences. It is rooted in the argument (elaborated below) that leadership experiences are a major route in the
development of leaders (Avolio,1999, 2005; Avolio & Gibbons,1988; Chan & Drasgow, 2001; Day, 2000; Day et al., 2004; London, 2002;
McCall, Lombardo & Morrison,1988). All major theories of learning and developmental psychological processes explicitly or implicitly
place experience at the center of the learning process. For example, the learning theories generally identiﬁed withSkinner (1989)are
based on the law of effect, that is, behavior is guided by past results. If in the past a certain behavior was rewarded, thereby receiving
positive reinforcement, the probability of that behavior appearing in the future is higher, while behaviors that were not rewarded will
probably appear less and less, and may even disappear.
Aspects such as self-efﬁcacy also develop on the basis of experiences.Bandura (1977, 1986), for example, showed that the sense of
success based on experiences in certain areas led to the strengthening of self-efﬁcacy in those areas. These principles proved relevant
and applicable to the area of leadership development. For example,Akin (1987), Kotter (1988),a n dMcCall et al. (1988)reported that
managers retrospectively viewed practical experience as a cardinal learning experience in their development as leaders. Successful
experiences in leadership roles, whether in the family framework or in educational or social frameworks, show the individual that he or
she is perceived by others as a leader; they also strengthen the individual's own belief in his or her ability to be a leader. Leaders'
testimonies reveal that personal experience was an important element in their learning of leadership (Chan & Drasgow, 2001; Day, Sin,
& Chen, 2004; Kotter, 1988, 1990). Atwater, Dionne, Avolio, Camobreco, and Leu (1999), seeking predictors of leadership, examined a
large number of mental and physical characteristics of freshmen at a military academy. They found that past leadership experiences
and self-efﬁcacy differentiated levels of leadership most clearly: students with a rich background of leadership experiences and high
self-efﬁcacy belonged to the highest level of leadership. Similarly,Hall et al. (2004)found in a longitudinal study of leadership that
West Point cadets who had had more leadership experiences at high school showed higher initial leadership performance at West
Point.Lord and Hall (2005)argue that leadership development via experiences can be described in terms of qualitative changes in both
process and knowledge as skills develop from the novice to the expert level (e.g.,Ericson & Charness, 1994). These changes involve
development of a large repertoire of more targeted, domain-speciﬁc productions rather than the general heuristics applied to all
Fig. 1.The general conceptual causal research model.
752 M. Popper, K. Amit / The Leadership Quarterly 20 (2009) 749–763
superﬁcially similar situations. In addition to guiding behaviors and social perceptions, this experience-based knowledge of leadership
becomes over time inextricably integrated with the development of one's self-concept as a leader.
Similarly,Sternberg (1981)highlights the notion oftacit knowledge(TK)— a form of implicit knowledge that helps the individual to
solve real-world, practical problems. To acquire tacit knowledge, however, an individual must have been exposed to the knowledge via
experience. Experience-based knowledge facilitates performance by allowing individuals to deﬁne the novel problems they face in an
environment functionally similar to the one in which they acquired the knowledge.Sternberg, Wagner, Williams, and Horvath (1995)
found that TK distinguished more from less successful performers in several domains, including sales, bank management, and clerical
work. TK was recently applied to research in the domain of military leadership (Hedlund et al., 2003). The results indicated that
domain-speciﬁc TK could explain individual differences in leadership experiences. In fact,Cianciolo, Antonakis, and Sternberg (2004)
suggest that an experience can be used as a“mentor”, fostering the creation of meaningful new knowledge based on past experiences.
In sum, leadership experiences, according to various scholars, are an important key to the development of both leadership skills and
self-efﬁcacy, as well as to the development of the cognitive and affective capacities vital for the successful functioning of a leader.
Our hypothesis is that the more an individual is characterized by a low level of trait anxiety and a higher level of openness to
experiences, the more he or she will undergo experiences relevant to the development of leadership. This general hypothesis was
examined speciﬁcally by two lines in the general model (Fig. 1), H3 and H4:
H3. A negative relation will be found between levels of trait anxiety and leadership experiences.
H4. A positive relation will be found between openness to experiences and leadership experiences.
Figs. 1 and 2present our suggested model represented by hypotheses one to four. In addition,ﬁve alternative causal models were
tested. Model 2 adds a direct line between secure attachment and leadership experience, and model 3 suggests that all three
independent variables (secure attachment, trait anxiety and openness to experiences) are directly related to the dependent variable—
leadership experience. We also tested the possibilities in which trait anxiety was the independent variable (model 4) and openness to
