experience was the independent variable (model 5). Finally, we tested an alternative model in which the independent variable
consisted of trait anxiety and secure attachment (model 6). Although it is outside the theoretical claim, we also tested the possibility
that leadership experiences in childhood may predict attachment style.
3. The research
3.1. Participants
The research took place in the Israel Defense Forces (IDF). The participants were 286 male soldiers (who formed a
representative sample of the entire cohort in compulsory army service) toward the end of their basic training. They belonged to
four companies: two from the armored corps (169 soldiers) and two from the infantry (117). The soldiers volunteered to
participate and anonymity was assured. Self-report questionnaires were administered to the participants. The response from the
armored companies was 65% and from the infantry 55%. Between 10% and 20% of the soldiers in the various platoons were new
immigrants who had language difﬁculties answering the questionnaires and were excluded from the sample. Other soldiers who
did not participate were absent for technical reasons (on duty, sick leave, etc.), and it may be assumed that they were omitted at
random. Prior to the research, a pilot study was conducted on 195 recruits in the armored corps and the infantry; that study served
as the basis for examination of the questionnaires.
1
3.2. Research instruments
3.2.1. Attachment style questionnaire
Attachment styles among adults are measured in research in two ways (Bartholomew & Shaver, 1998), one based on a clinical
interview and the other on quantitative measures developed consequent toHazan and Shaver's pioneering work (1987)on
attachment and romantic relations. Hazan and Shaver's work stemmed from the assumption that chronically lonely people who
constantly seek romantic relations and regularly fail in them in fact reﬂect a late expression of insecure attachment styles in early
childhood. Hazan and Shaver developed a self-report questionnaire based on the three attachment styles ofAinsworth et al.
(1978). In responding to the questionnaire, people were asked to think of romantic situations in their past and to indicate which
statements, referring to the three styles, were the most descriptive of themselves.
In subsequent studies this measure and several variants have been used for a host of close relationships. Some studies have
correlated this measure with retrospective reports of childhood experiences with parents. The bulk of research in this tradition has
focused on the inﬂuence of attachment patterns on personal adjustment and adult relationships (for reviews seeRholes &
Simpson, 2004).
Hazan and Shaver (1987) showed that the distribution of attachment styles of the adults in their study was similar to that
found among the infants (Ainsworth et al., 1978), with 56% reporting a secure attachment style, 24% an avoidant style, and
20% an anxious/avoidant style. A similar distribution was found in various other studies conducted among adults; also, as
described above, attachment style was found to predict other affective relations that are measurable among adults (e.g.,
Collins & Read, 1990; Feeney et al., 1994; Mikulincer & Orbach, 1995). These studies validated statistically the argument that
attachment styles formed in early childhood can indeed be reﬂected by measurement in a questionnaire for adults.
In recent years there has been some criticism of the instrument developed byHazan and Shaver (1987). The general argument
is that the typology of three supposedly distinct types cannot encompass the variety and complexity of the attachment schemas.
Factor analyses performed in various studies yielded two mega-dimensions that help to explain individual differences in
attachment: avoidance and anxiety (e.g.,Fraley & Waller, 1998; Shaver, Belsky, & Brennan, 2000). The anxiety dimension is
characterized by constant worry about relationships, fear of loneliness, and fear of abandonment. The avoidance dimension is
characterized by discomfort with closeness and dependence, avoidance of expression of emotion, and extreme self-reliance. Low
scores on anxiety and avoidance characterize the secure style. This measurement method is the most widely used today in research
on individual differences in attachment tendencies, and this was the approach we used in the present study. We calculated the
secure score on the 13 items characterizing the anxious (6 items) and the avoidant (7 items), so those who were neither anxious
nor avoidant were secure (a typical item measuring attachment anxiety:“I worry about being abandoned.” A typical avoidant
attachment item:“I prefer not to show a partner how I feel deep down.”)
3.2.2. Trait anxiety inventory
This inventory presents 20 statements that reﬂect the respondent's general anxiety level (Spielberger, Gorsuch, & Lushene,
1970). The respondent is asked to rate the degree to which he or she generally feels each emotion on a four-point scale from
“almost never” to “almost always” (typical items:“I often get tired”, “I am often sad”). After reversal of the items, the scores on the
questionnaire range between 20 and 80, the higher score indicating a higher level of trait anxiety. The test–retest reliability of the
1 To test the various instruments used in the research we conducted a pilot study, from February to the end of October 2002, with the participation of 195
soldiers from one armored corps company. First a series of self-report questionnaires was administered to the soldiers, who were approaching the end of their
basic training (approximately two months in the army). At the second stage we returned two weeks later to 28 of the soldiers (approx. 14%) for a semi-structured
in-depth interview. At the third stage (May 2002) we went back to the soldiers yet again, and administered the questionnaires to test their stability.
754 M. Popper, K. Amit / The Leadership Quarterly 20 (2009) 749–763
questionnaire, as reported in the manual, is .73. Internal consistency reliability tests yielded Cronbach's alpha values between .89
and .91 (Teichmann & Melinek, 1979).
3.2.3. Questionnaire on openness to new experiences
To examine the degree of openness to experiences, the research team developed a questionnaire based on the NEO-PI-R
Personality Inventory (Costa & McCrae, 1992a). It examinesﬁve personality factors (the Big Five), one of which is openness to new
experiences. In the Hebrew version of the questionnaire this factor is examined by 48 items (Montag & Levin,1994). The respondent
is asked to indicate how far he or she agrees with each statement (typical statements:“I often think differently from others”, “I like
surprises”). Replies are given on aﬁve-point Likert scale from“strongly disagree” to “strongly agree.” Cronbach's alpha reliability
coefﬁcient on the“openness to experience” factor in this Hebrew version was .65. Our research team developed an abbreviated
questionnaire, Openness to Experiences(OE), comprising 24 items. The main reasons for constructing the new questionnaire were
the need to shorten the original one due to the limited time available for administering it in the army setting, and the need to modify
the language to make it more comprehensible to the soldiers. The general score on this measure can range from 24 to 120.
The new questionnaire (OE) was validated against the Hebrew version of the original questionnaire (NEO-PI-R) by administration
of both questionnaires to 113 respondents, men and women, most of them (65%) students at Haifa University, the rest attending
preparatory courses (for admission to the university). Cronbach's alpha reliability coefﬁcient of the new questionnaire was .64, and a
signiﬁcant correlation (r=.7 7 ,pb.01) was found between the scores of the original and the new questionnaire. The latter was
examined in the context of the pilot study, and its reliability level was found acceptable and matching the level reported in the
literature (see footnote 1).
3.2.4. Leadership development questionnaire
To examine the development of leadership we used a questionnaire that we constructed to examine leadership-shaping
experiences (LSE) from childhood to conscription in the military. The questionnaire was composed on the basis ofAvolio and Gibbons'
(1988) measure, and incorporated other issues that proved central in semi-structured interviews conducted in the pilot study (see
footnote 1).
The logic behind the construction of this measure was the possibility of quantifying issues previously investigated by qualitative
methods (Amit et al., 2008). Leadership experiences was measured by seven questions (on aﬁve-point Likert scale) indicating the
extent of responsibility and inﬂuence (i.e., roles, duties, tasks) respondents experienced at home, at school, and in social frameworks.
The questions were: To what extent did you feel during your childhood that your parents or others around you encouraged you
to inﬂuence others? To what extent were you given responsibility at home (taking care of younger children, household chores,
etc.)? At junior high school and high school, to what extent did you have roles that included certain responsibilities (class
committee, students' council)? To what extent did you like to undertake organizational tasks at school? To what extent did you try
to change things in your school? To what extent did you have any experience of leadership roles in other social frameworks? How
would you deﬁne the experience you accumulated? (1=hardly any experience–5=rich experience).
3.3. Analysis method
The reliability of the research instruments was tested and the relations between the research variables were examined by
means of a correlation matrix. We used Structural Equation Modeling with AMOS 5 software (Byrne, 2001) to test the
hypothesized models. FollowingAnderson and Garbing's (1988)two-step approach, we tested the measurement modelﬁrst, and
then the structural causal model.
The measurement model assesses whether all items on a given scale represent the same latent construct. A rule of thumb is that
a
measurement model with three indicators per latent construct is ideal, and it can carry up toﬁve indicators without estimation
difﬁculties (Bagozzi & Heatherton, 1994). When more thanﬁve items measure the same construct, a parceling procedure can be
used to combine items randomly into composites (Bagozzi & Heatherton, 1994). Parceling reduces random errors and simpliﬁes
the model while simultaneously maintaining the integrity of multiple-indicator measurement. We used parceling procedures for
all the variables in the models. Each of our variable measures had more thanﬁve items. In each measure these were randomly
parceled into three composite indicators, which were entered into the measurement and structural models as multiple indicators
to estimate the latent constructs.
The structural model provides maximum likelihood estimates of all identiﬁed model parameters, and evaluates the degree to which
the model reproduces the observed variance–covariance matrix in terms of a chi-square goodness-of-ﬁt statistic (Bollen & Long,1993).
This method enabled us to test theﬁt of the correlation matrix against alternative models. Our research model (model 1) suggests that
the secure attachment style inﬂuences the trait anxiety level and openness to experiences level; these two variables, in turn, affect the
dependent leadership variable. This research model is based on the assumption that certain psychological phenomena expressed in
later development arise from the internal representations formed during attachment in early infancy. This assumption was supported,
for example, in the longitudinal Minnesota studies (Elicker et al., 1992) and in cross-sectional studies on attachment (Englund et al.,
2000; Isabella, 1993; Isabella & Belsky, 1991). This is the theoretical basis for numerous studies on the prediction of emotional
phenomena in adults (see, for example,Rholes & Simpson, 2004). The SEM model, which serves a conﬁrmatory analysis for theory
testing, is thus an adequate method for testing this theoretical claim. In addition to the main model, we have tested all other alternative
models mentioned earlier.
