4. Results
The reliability scores of the research instruments and the correlation coefﬁcients of the variables (constructs) under study are
presented in Table 1. The instrument's reliability scores were sufﬁcient, as compared to the relevant scores reported in the
literature. Correlations between the variables went in the directions hypothesized: signiﬁcant negative correlations between trait
anxiety, openness to experiences, secure attachment style and leadership experiences; signiﬁcant positive correlations between all
the other variables: secure attachment style, openness to experiences, and leadership experiences.
4.1. Measurement model
The results from our measurement model indicate that the modelﬁtted the data well. A non-signiﬁcant χ2 (51.97; df =48;
p=.32) was obtained, indicating that the model ﬁtted the data. Other ﬁt statistics were excellent (CFI=.996, NFI=.95,
NNFI=.994, GFI=.96, RMSA=.02). Factor loadings ranged from 0.59 to 0.86, in support of the model's measurement properties,
and correlations between the constructs ranged from .21 to .61 and were signiﬁcant. All these measures indicated good modelﬁt,
with satisfactory convergent and discriminant validity. Hence, we could proceed to the next step.
4.2. Structural model
Six structural models were tested and the results are presented inFigs. 2–7, followingHoyle's (1995)recommendations. For
each model the results are presented in diagrams with speciﬁcation of the main statistical measures: regression weights, multiple
correlation coefﬁcients, andﬁt measures of each structural model.
Our hypothesized model, model 1,ﬁtted the data well, as shown in theﬁt measures: a non-signiﬁcant χ2 was obtained (57.3;
df =50; p=.22), indicating that the modelﬁtted the data, allﬁt indexes exceeded .90, and RMSEA was signiﬁcant (pb.05).
Fig. 2 presents our structural model graphically, making it possible to test the research hypotheses. According to H1, a
negative correlation would be found between secure attachment style and high level of trait anxiety. Theﬁndings fully
supported this hypothesis, with a signiﬁcant (p b.01) and strong negative relationship between secure attachment and trait
anxiety (β=−.62). H2 posited that a positive relation would be found between secure attachment style and openness to
experiences. The ﬁndings supported this hypothesis, with a signi ﬁcant (p b.01) positive relationship between secure
attachment and openness to experiences (β=.24). According to H3, a negative relation would be found between levels of trait
anxiety and leadership experiences. This hypothesis was supported, with a signiﬁcant (p b.01) negative relation between trait
anxiety and leadership experiences (β=−.23). Theﬁndings also supported the next hypothesis, H4: a positive relation would
be found between openness to experiences and leadership experiences. A signiﬁcant (p b.01) positive relation was indeed found
here (β=.34).
Model 1, depicted inFig. 2, support our hypothesis, showing that secure attachment style directly affects the levels of trait
anxiety and openness to experiences, and these two basic components affect leadership experiences. This model explained 19% of
the variance of the leadership parameter.
As mentioned, other alternative models were tested. In model 2, a direct line was added between secure attachment and leadership
experiences. As presented inFig. 3, the modelﬁtted the data well: a non-signiﬁcant χ2 was obtained (54.77;df=49; p=.27), allﬁt
indexes exceeded .90, and the RMSEA was signiﬁcant (pb.05). However, the additional direct relation between secure attachment and
leadership experiences was not signiﬁcant (β=. 1 8,p=.12). Moreover, the relation between trait anxiety and leadership experiences
was not signiﬁcant (β=−.11,pN.05).
To test the differences between the two models a chi-square difference test was conducted and was found not signiﬁcant
(χ2 =2. 36,df=1 ,p=.12). Theseﬁndings suggest that this alternative model made no signiﬁcant contribution and was less adequate
in explaining the relations between the variables.
Another alternative model suggested that three independent variables (secure attachment, trait anxiety and openness to
experiences) were directly related to the dependent variable (model 3). As presented inFig. 4,t h em o d e ld i dn o tﬁt the data well:
as i g n iﬁcant χ2 was obtained (132.1;df =5 1;p =.00), most ﬁt indexes did not exceed .90, and the RMSEA was not signiﬁcant
(p N.05). In this model the relationship between trait anxiety and leadership experiences was not signiﬁcant. We tried to improve
this model by adding correlations between all three independent variables, but although theﬁt of the model was improved only
the relation between openness to experiences and leadership experiences was found signiﬁcant. Theseﬁndings suggest that this
alternative model is not adequate.
