In model 4, anxiety is the main independent variable predicting the secure attachment style and openness to experiences, and these
two variables in turn predict leadership experiences.
Model 4ﬁtted the data well: a non-signiﬁcant χ2 was obtained (52.55;df=49; p=.34), all ﬁt indexes exceeded .90, and the
RMSEA was signiﬁcant (pb.05). However, two direct relations proved not signiﬁcant: the relation between anxiety and leadership
experiences (β=−.08, pN.05) and the relation between secure attachment and leadership experiences (β=.2 1,p =.07). Still, the
ﬁt of this alternative model indicates that anxiety is negatively and signiﬁcantly related to secure attachment style.
To test whether openness to experience may be the main independent variable predicting attachment and anxiety we tested
another alternative, model 5, presented inFig. 6.
Model 5 did notﬁt the data as well as model 4: a signiﬁcant χ2 was obtained (113.5;df=49; p=.00), someﬁt indexes did not
exceed .90, and the RMSEA was not signiﬁcant (pN.05). The relationship between trait anxiety and leadership experiences (β=−.11,
pN.05), as well as that between attachment and leadership experiences (β=. 1 7,p =.06), were not signiﬁcant.
To test the possibility that leadership experiences in childhood and adolescence predict attachment style as well as anxiety and
openness to experience, another model was examined. This one did notﬁt the data well: a signiﬁcant χ2 was obtained (108.25;
df =5 1;p=.00), most ﬁt indexes did not exceed .90 (NNFI=.88, NFI=.92, RFI=.85, CFI=.93), the RMSEA was not signiﬁcant
(pN.05), and ECVI score was .69.
Comparing ECVI scores for each of the alternative models indicated that the three bestﬁtting were models 1, 2 and 4 (χ2
differences between each pair of models cannot be checked since the models are not nested). These three models had the lowest
ECVI scores (since model 2 was found not signiﬁcantly different from model 1, we refer only to model 1). Model 1, our suggested
model, shows that secure attachment is the main independent variable, whereas according to model 4 anxiety is the main
independent variable. Thisﬁnding may indicate that the relation between secure attachment and anxiety could represent a mutual
causal effect. We tried to test such a model using a causal arrow between anxiety and secure attachment going in either direction
(retaining all other variables in the model), but the model obtained was non-recursive with a stability index of 1.842. According to
