5. Discussion
This study was based on a hierarchical assumption that a psychological substructure formed in early childhood gives rise to the
basic components that later inﬂuence the intensity and scope of development of leadership via experiences. This argument was
tested by structural equation modeling (SEM), a procedure that facilitates assessment of the validity of the measures in the model
as well as the hypothesized causal path.
The study was designed to examine as a preliminary hypothesis our assumption of the formation of a psychological
substructure for the basic components. Attachment theory (Bowlby, 1969) – and secure attachment style as a measurable
expression of processes described in this theory– served as the theoretical framework for prediction of the formation of the basic
components, trait anxiety and openness to experiences, in early childhood.
Six alternative models assumed to predict leadership experiences were presented and tested (the possibility that leadership
experiences is the independent variable was also tested and ruled out). The results support our original hypothesis (model 1)
showing that secure attachment style directly affects the levels of trait anxiety and openness to experiences, and these two basic
components are related to leadership experiences. This model explained 19% of the variance of the leadership parameter. The
direct relation between secure attachment and leadership experiences added in model 2 was not signiﬁcant (β=. 1 8,p =.12). Nor
Fig. 4.Leadership development pattern: research model 3 (N=238).
758 M. Popper, K. Amit / The Leadership Quarterly 20 (2009) 749–763
was the relation between trait anxiety and leadership experiences. Model 3, in which secure attachment, trait anxiety and
openness to experiences were directly related to the dependent variable was found inadequate. Model 5, in which openness to
experience was the independent variable, was also found inadequate. However, trait anxiety (presented in model 4) proved
signiﬁcant in predicting secure attachment and openness to experience. That is, two of the tested models can be seen as
competing: the original model, in which the independent variable is secure attachment style, or the model in which trait anxiety is
the basis of the causal model. Model six suggests not seeing these two variables in terms of causal relationships but seeing both of
them as the infrastructure of the entire model leading to prediction of the dependent variable .This perspective is consistent with
competing views regarding the formation of general (“trait”) anxiety. One claims that anxiety is mostly learned (Izard, 1977). This
approach allows more psychological developmental explanations (such as attachment theory) in which anxiety is formed as a
result of certain forms of interactions occurring mostly in early childhood. This approach is largely supported by clinical
psychologists (see reviews bySpielberger, 1979; Barlow, 1988).
The other approach deals with anxiety in terms of genetic, psychophysiological and neurobiological aspects (Selye,1976)o rb i o l o g i c a l
theories of personality emphasizing different levels or intensities of biological variables such as cortical arousal ( e.g.Eysenck, 1981)o r
other heritable tendencies such as an active behavioral inhibition system (e.g.Cloninger 1986).
The results in this study cannot determine whether anxiety is more learned or more innate. However, the negative signiﬁcant
correlation found between trait anxiety and secure attachment style (Figs. 2, 3, 5 and 7) can be meaningful in an analysis of the
development of central emotional capacities which have been widely studied in attachment research and are important in
maintaining effective leadership. For example, as mentioned in the review, it was found that a person who is secure has a better
capacity for intimacy in romantic relations (Hazan & Shaver, 1987) and a better quality of friendship relations (Mayseless et al.,
1997). These ﬁndings are congruent with studies indicating a positive correlation between secure attachment style and the
developing factor in the factorial structure of transformational leadership— individualized consideration (Popper et al., 2000;
Davidovitz et al., 2007). Common to all theseﬁndings is the development of affective capacity, which, asKellet, Humphrey, and
Sleeth (2006)assert, is central to (close) leader–followers relationships. The ability to identify others' emotions and the ability to
Fig. 5.Leadership development pattern: research model 4 (N=236).
759M. Popper, K. Amit / The Leadership Quarterly 20 (2009) 749–763
display one's own emotions are reported as crucial in developing effective leader–member relations (Newcomb & Ashkanasy,
2002). Of particular importance to such relationships is the ability to extend empathy, that is,“the ability to comprehend another's
feelings and to re-experience them oneself” (Salovey & Mayer, 1990, pp. 194–195). Goleman, Boyatzis, and McKee (2002, p. 50)
state that empathy is“the fundamental competence of social awareness.”They argue that effective leaders create a“resonance”
with their followers, and by doing so they can guide their followers to more productive emotional responses and work behavior. So
emotional qualities that are necessary for the existence of social relations of any kind seem also relevant to leadership relations.
The secure attachment style seems to predict the functions that are characterized by a higher quality of interaction with other
people in a variety of relationships. Ourﬁndings strengthen this theoretical position and support what appears to be a promising
direction in looking at leadership as a certain type of emotional relationship (Popper, 2004).
The negative signiﬁcant correlations found between trait anxiety and openness to experience (Figs. 5 and 6) might also add
information that can be interpreted in developmental terms by using the attachment theory perspective. It is reported in
attachment studies that a person can afford to explore the environment and new experiences because of the general sense of a
secure base (Ainsworth et al., 1978) and also because of a high sense of efﬁcacy (Carnelley & Ruscher, 2000; Cassidy, 1999; Hazan &
Shaver, 1990). Theseﬁndings are congruent with reports on correlations between openness to experiences and leadership, using
the Big Five model (Costa & McCrea, 1992a; Judge et al., 2002).
All our researchﬁndings indicate on the centrality of trait anxiety and openness to experience to leaders' development via
experiences. Although more exploration is needed on whether these variables are more acquired (e.gBowlby, 1969) or more innate
(Cloninger, 1986), theﬁndings still indicate that individuals are likely equipped with differential developmental substructures that
might affect leadership development. Moreover, the attempt made in this study to link conceptualizations and studies in
developmental psychology and the study of leadership development is far from exhausted. Future studies should also deal with the
issue of motivation to lead, an aspect that has been neglected in the psychological study of leadership (Chan & Drasgow, 2001);
only recently have some attempts been made to deal with it (Kark & Van Dijk, 2007; Popper & Mayseless, 2002). So far these
attempts have been mostly theoretical, and much more empirical work needs to be done. The assumption is that not all of those
Fig. 6.Leadership development pattern: research model 5 (N=236).
760 M. Popper, K. Amit / The Leadership Quarterly 20 (2009) 749–763
who have basic developmental components for leadership will necessarily want to be leaders, just as people who have abilities in
any other area may not want to engage in it and therefore will not endeavor to develop those abilities. This naturally has
developmental implications.
